Hypothesis 1

friends_vs_happiness <- responses %>% select( Number.of.friends, Happiness.in.life) %>% arrange(desc(Number.of.friends)) 

plot( jitter (Number.of.friends) ~ jitter( Happiness.in.life), data = friends_vs_happiness)

# there does seem to be a relationship between number of friends and happiness, because those who had more friends typically were more happy, and there were very few people who had little friends and were very happy.

“Hypothesis 2”

 gender_vs_happiness <- select(responses, Gender, Happiness.in.life)

 boxplot( Happiness.in.life ~ Gender, data = gender_vs_happiness, main="")

#I dont think there is a relationship between gender and happiness because the boxplot shows an equal boxplot between male and female for happiness.

Hypothesis 3

happiness_vs_age <- select(responses, Age, Happiness.in.life) %>% filter(!is.na(Happiness.in.life)) %>% arrange(Age) %>% group_by(Age) %>% summarise(avg_happiness = mean(Happiness.in.life))
plot( avg_happiness ~ Age, data = happiness_vs_age)

#It appears as if people get happier on average as they get older each year.

Hypothesis 4

music_happiness <- select(responses, Happiness.in.life, Music)
plot( jitter(Happiness.in.life) ~ jitter(Music), data = music_happiness)

# Music seems to have a direct impact on people’s lives, because typically people who were happiest in life liked music the most. However, most people did not say they did not like music at all, or even very little. People were ultimately clustered into liking music a lot, even if they were unhappy.

Hypothesis 5

Age_regret <- responses %>% mutate(choices = Decision.making / Self.criticism) %>% select (Age, choices)
plot( jitter(Age) ~ jitter(choices), data = Age_regret)

#This shows that many young people rarely take their time to make a decision, owing to how often the numbers are less than one. Most of the numbers are grouped around 1 or less than 1, meaning that to get that, most of the people both rarely take time to make a decision and often regret the decisions they make. This fades out as people become younger.

Hypothesis 6

Funny_fake <- select(responses, Funniness, Fake)
plot( jitter(Funniness) ~ jitter(Fake), data = Funny_fake)

#This graph shows that the more fake a person is, the less funny they seem. However, someone who is not funny does not influence whether or not a person is fake.
